Square Sequences
Write a function that takes the numbers 1 through n and, if possible, orders them in such a way that each pair of consecutive elements adds up to a square number.
More Details
There are many ways of ordering the whole numbers 1 through n. For example, here is one of the ways for n=15:
PermutationList[RandomPermutation[15]]
{3,15,6,8,10,1,9,14,13,4,11,2,5,7,12}
In fact, the number of ways is the product of the numbers from 1 to n, which is written as n! =nÃ(n-1)Ã(n-2)Ãâ¦Ã3Ã2Ã1. (Read n! as "n factorial".)
15!
1307674368000
Sometimes some of those sequences have special properties. For example, arrange the numbers 1 through 15 in the following way:
arr={8,1,15,10,6,3,13,12,4,5,11,14,2,7,9};
The sum of any two consecutive terms of arr is always a perfect square!
Most[arr]+Rest[arr]
